{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"34a14216-0f7d-4b2a-8462-ee0ac23c4ced","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Tests appear as new (no history)\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID algorithm**. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so every test looks brand-new. To restore history, add this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nOr, if you want to move forward with the new IDs, accept a one-time history reset.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — no test is running yet, so `TestName` throws. In v3 it misleadingly returned the first test's name.\n\nYour fix for `SetupTests.cs` — remove the `TestName` access from class init:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Y7hj4dyv3yjXx5DQhDfywN","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-d8d6ecb4f23745279718e8f916686c35/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4, TestContext in [ClassInitialize] is class-scoped;\n        // TestName is only available in [TestInitialize] or test methods.\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-d8d6ecb4f23745279718e8f916686c35/SetupTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"267975e9-9568-4567-9542-61560d0056ea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can see the user's code. Let me address their questions about MSTest v4 breaking changes based on my knowledge:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps (no history)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation changed. The fully qualified test name format was updated, which means Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests. This is a known breaking change.\n\n2. **`TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]` throwing**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a class-level context, not tied to any specific test. Accessing `TestName` on it throws because there's no test running yet at class initialization time. \n\nIn v3, this would have returned the name of the first test to run, though that was arguably misleading behavior. Beyond these issues, there are several other migration concerns: the unified `MSTest` package now consolidates what used to be three separate packages, `TestContext` properties aren't available in class-level contexts, timeout defaults have shifted, and attributes like `DataRow`, `DynamicData`, and `DeploymentItem` have behavioral changes. Test parallelization defaults may also differ from what you're used to.","outputTokens":789,"requestId":"67C5:1F50C6:1CB1F7B:205356B:69FD5452"},"id":"de7bec86-74d3-4551-af74-af8098b57d41","timestamp":"2026-05-08T03:11:32.115Z","parentId":"0b546324-c814-424c-9af6-dd54d289a500"}
